## Section 1 
Francesca Beaumont explores the immense race and expansion of worldwide AI development, down to the microchips that allow it all

Author info: Written by Francesca Beaumont, a Data and AI Ethics Masters student, whose predominant academic interest is on developing ethical frameworks for the responsible integration of multi-model Agentic AI systems into the financial sector.

(Originally on my Universities Science Magazine)

In the global race to have monopoly over the AI industry, it’s often posited that ‘whoever has the best algorithms and the most data wins.’ As the world ties its social and political advancement to digital development, the race for market dominance will only accelerate.

As of late 2025, the US remains the primary site for Generative AI development, with tech-giants like OpenAI and Google DeepMind driving the global economic market. In comparison, East Asia is prioritising a widespread integration of robotics and AI-assistive technology into everyday life at a rate the West is yet to catch up to.

Against such global speed, Europe sits in stark contrast; despite the fact that the EU is ‘working to increase its advantage over other regions in the industry,’ it is still struggling to match the scale and supply of our global counterparts. The difficulty Europe faces is not solely down to funding, but compounded by stressed timing and lack of industrial depth. Advanced fabrication plants cost tens of billions to construct and require a dense ecosystem of suppliers, specialist labourers, and reliable energy infrastructures; clusters that already exist in the United States and Asia.

The most tangible attempt to close this infrastructure gap has been the 2023 ‘EU Chips Act’. This is a €43 billion initiative developed to ‘reinforce the semiconductor ecosystem in the EU’, by investing in chip design, pilot lines, and research & development networks, thus manufacturing advanced resilience across European supply chains.

With AI’s rapid acceleration it’s easy to ascribe a sense of innovative wonder to such development, but this mysticism is managed and maintained by microchips. These microscopic panels of silicon are semiconductors that drive new machine learning models (MLMs). Every generated image, chatbot reply, and algorithm is dependent on billions of microscopic circuits, switching on and off at unimaginable speeds.

A microchip is essentially a miniaturised landscape of electronic switches that control the flow of a complex current. Chips can hold tens of billions of these switches known as transistors. Working across a large supply chain, these chips create intricate pathways that enable computation and make AI appear seamless.

