Against the race for market dominance, semiconductors are no longer just industrial components, but strategic assets used to reify a nation’s position within the global AI market. Chips underpin the modern economy, meaning disruptions in the chain can have a massive impact on a country’s economic standing. Whoever controls the microchips controls the pace of global innovation.

The Chips Act functions as both strategic industrial development and ‘geopolitical insurance’, strengthening European independence and reducing reliance on global supply. However, the site for Artificial Infrastructure is still lagging far behind globally. To secure dominance, Europe will need to translate its regulatory leadership into more advanced manufacturing capability.

In this context, the EU Chips Act is less an attempt at immediate AI leadership and more so an endeavour to reduce vulnerability; ensuring that Europe is not overly exposed to external threats and geopolitical pressure.

