Noted by the Centre for Strategic and International Studies, ‘the semiconductor industry and its supply chain increasingly rival oil and gas in terms of their importance to international relations.’ Computerised microchips are mutually inclusive with global macroeconomics and wield unprecedented influence on the race to be the frontrunners for the next wave of Artificial Intelligence.

Even at the University of Edinburgh, researchers in the School of Informatics are working on ‘developing a wafer-chip system which could help AI draw conclusions from data ten times faster.’ Given the material significance of microchip technology, the research has been described as an ‘exemplar of how to effectively design software.’

As AI continues to evolve at pace, its market power rests not only on data and algorithms, but on the microchips that sustain them. These miniature microchips are of central importance to the global AI market, which depends as much on control over physical infrastructure as on the advances in software.

To gain a sustained monopoly over AI in the global market, it is essential to balance having just as much control over innovation and code as over the physical infrastructure that is used to sustain such software.

